  "prompt": "I'm a rookie. How should I start preparing for getting selected in GSoC 17?",
  "response": "Okay, you're a rookie aiming for Google Summer of Code (GSoC) 2017. That's fantastic!  While GSoC 2017 has long passed, the general process for future GSoCs remains largely the same.  Here's a step-by-step guide on how to prepare for a GSoC-like program in the future. Since GSoC is an annual program, it's a continuous process of preparation.  This guidance is applicable for GSoC, or other similar Open Source project contribution programs.\n\n**Phase 1: Laying the Foundation (Now - Several Months Before GSoC Season)**\n\nThis phase is all about building your skills and getting familiar with the open-source world.  This is the most important phase.\n\n1. **Choose Your Technology Focus:**\n\n   *   **Identify Your Interests:** What programming languages, technologies, and fields genuinely excite you?  Web development, machine learning, systems programming, mobile apps, game development, data science? Pick something you enjoy, or you'll lose motivation.\n   *   **Learn the Basics:**  If you're a complete beginner, start with the fundamentals of programming.  Python, C++, Java, JavaScript are common choices.  Many excellent online courses (Coursera, edX, freeCodeCamp, Codecademy, Khan Academy) are available. Don't jump straight to advanced topics. Solid fundamentals are key.\n   *   **Intermediate Skills:** Learn Data Structures and Algorithms, design patterns and coding best practices.\n   *   **Practice Regularly:** Coding is a skill; you need to practice consistently.  Solve problems on platforms like LeetCode, HackerRank, Codewars, or Project Euler.\n   *   **Build Small Projects:**  Don't just follow tutorials; build your own small projects to apply what you've learned.  A simple web app, a command-line tool, a basic game \u2013 anything to solidify your understanding.\n\n2. **Explore Open Source:**\n\n   *   **Understand the Philosophy:**  Read about the open-source movement, its principles, and its benefits.\n   *   **GitHub Account:** Create a GitHub account. This is essential.  Learn how to use Git for version control (commit, push, pull, branch, merge, pull requests).  There are many excellent Git tutorials online.\n   *   **Explore Repositories:**  Browse GitHub, GitLab, and other open-source platforms.  Look for projects that align with your interests.  Start by looking at projects you *use*.  Read the code.  Try to understand how they work.  Don't be intimidated if you don't understand everything at first.\n   *   **Find Good First Issues:** Many projects label easier issues as \"good first issue\" or \"beginner-friendly.\"  These are designed for newcomers to contribute.  Start with these.\n\n3. **Start Contributing (Early and Often):**\n\n   *   **Documentation:** Fix typos, improve explanations, add examples. This is a great way to get your feet wet and learn the project's structure.\n   *   **Bug Fixes:**  Look for reported bugs and try to fix them.  Start with simple ones.\n   *   **Small Features:** Implement small, well-defined features.\n   *   **Code Review:** Offer to review pull requests from other contributors.  This is a great way to learn from others and improve your understanding of the project.\n   *   **Be Respectful and Professional:**  Follow the project's contribution guidelines.  Write clear and concise commit messages.  Be patient and responsive to feedback.  Open source communities value collaboration.\n\n**Phase 2: Deep Dive (Closer to GSoC Announcement)**\n\nThis phase is about targeting specific organizations and projects.\n\n1.  **Identify Potential Organizations:**\n\n    *   **GSoC Organization List (When Available):** Google publishes a list of participating organizations a few weeks before the application period opens.  Carefully review this list.\n    *   **Match Your Skills:**  Choose organizations whose projects align with your skills and interests.  Don't apply to organizations just because they are popular.\n    *   **Research Organizations:**  Visit the organization's website, GitHub repository, and communication channels (mailing lists, IRC, Slack, Gitter).  Understand their mission, their projects, and their community.\n\n2.  **Engage with the Community:**\n\n    *   **Introduce Yourself:**  Join the organization's communication channels and introduce yourself.  Explain your interests and your willingness to contribute.\n    *   **Ask Questions:**  Don't be afraid to ask questions.  Ask about the project, the codebase, the contribution process, and potential GSoC project ideas.  Show that you are genuinely interested and eager to learn.\n    *   **Help Others:**  Answer questions from other contributors, review their code, and offer your assistance.\n\n3. **Identify Project Ideas (or Propose Your Own):**\n\n   *   **Organization's Ideas List:**  Organizations usually provide a list of project ideas on their website or in their repository.  Review these carefully.\n   *   **Talk to Mentors:**  Discuss potential project ideas with mentors.  Get their feedback and suggestions.\n   *   **Propose Your Own:**  If you have your own project idea that aligns with the organization's goals, propose it.  Be sure to discuss it with mentors first. A good idea should solve a real problem, be feasible within the GSoC timeframe, and be something you are passionate about.\n\n**Phase 3: Proposal Writing (During the Application Period)**\n\nThis is a critical phase. Your proposal is your opportunity to convince the organization that you are the right person for the project.\n\n1.  **Understand the Requirements:**\n\n    *   **GSoC Guidelines:**  Carefully read the official GSoC guidelines.\n    *   **Organization's Requirements:**  Each organization has its own specific requirements for proposals.  Follow these meticulously.\n\n2.  **Structure of a Good Proposal:**\n\n    *   **Introduction:**  Briefly introduce yourself, your skills, and your interests.\n    *   **Project Summary:**  Clearly describe the project you are proposing.  What problem does it solve?  What are the goals?\n    *   **Detailed Plan:**  Break down the project into smaller tasks.  Provide a timeline for each task.  Be realistic about what you can accomplish in the GSoC timeframe (typically 12 weeks).\n    *   **Technical Details:**  Describe the technologies you will use, the challenges you anticipate, and how you plan to overcome them.  Show that you have a good understanding of the technical aspects of the project.\n    *   **Deliverables:**  Specify what you will deliver at the end of the GSoC period (e.g., code, documentation, tests).\n    *   **Timeline:** Provide a week-by-week timeline of your project, showing what you plan to accomplish each week.  This demonstrates that you have thought through the project carefully.\n    *   **About You:**  Highlight your relevant skills and experience.  Mention your previous contributions to the organization or other open-source projects.  Explain why you are a good fit for the project.\n    *   **Motivation:**  Express your enthusiasm for the project and your commitment to completing it.\n    *   **Contingency Plan:** What will you do if you encounter roadblocks or unexpected challenges? Showing you've thought about potential issues demonstrates foresight.\n\n3. **Write a Clear and Concise Proposal:**\n\n    *   **Be Specific:**  Avoid vague statements.  Provide concrete details.\n    *   **Be Realistic:**  Don't overpromise.  It's better to deliver less than you promised than to fail to deliver.\n    *   **Be Well-Organized:**  Use headings, subheadings, and bullet points to make your proposal easy to read.\n    *   **Proofread Carefully:**  Check for typos, grammatical errors, and inconsistencies.\n\n4. **Get Feedback:**\n\n   *   **Mentors:**  Share your proposal with mentors and ask for their feedback.  They can provide valuable insights and help you improve your proposal.\n   *   **Other Contributors:**  Ask other contributors to review your proposal.  A fresh pair of eyes can often spot errors or areas for improvement.\n\n5. **Submit Your Proposal:**\n\n   *   **Before the Deadline:**  Submit your proposal well before the deadline.  Don't wait until the last minute.\n   *   **Follow Instructions:**  Carefully follow the organization's instructions for submitting proposals.\n\n**Phase 4: Post-Submission (Waiting and Continuing to Contribute)**\n\n1. **Continue Contributing:**\n\n   *   **Stay Active:**  Even after submitting your proposal, continue to contribute to the organization.  This shows that you are genuinely interested and committed.\n   *   **Respond to Feedback:**  If the organization asks for clarification or additional information, respond promptly and thoroughly.\n\n2. **Be Patient:**\n\n   *   **Results Announcement:**  The results of GSoC are typically announced a few weeks after the application deadline.\n   *   **Don't Be Discouraged:**  If you are not selected, don't be discouraged.  Use the experience to learn and improve.  Continue to contribute to open source and apply again next year!  Many successful GSoC participants have applied multiple times.\n\n**Key Strategies for Success:**\n\n*   **Start Early:** The earlier you start preparing, the better your chances of success.\n*   **Be Proactive:** Don't wait for opportunities to come to you. Seek them out.\n*   **Be Persistent:** Don't give up easily. Open source can be challenging, but it is also rewarding.\n*   **Be a Good Community Member:**  Contribute to the community in a positive and helpful way.\n*   **Communicate Effectively:**  Clearly and concisely communicate your ideas and plans.\n*   **Learn from Your Mistakes:**  Everyone makes mistakes. Learn from them and improve.\n*   **Focus on Quality over Quantity:**  It's better to make a few high-quality contributions than many low-quality ones.\n*   **Be Passionate:**  Choose a project that you are genuinely interested in. Your enthusiasm will shine through in your contributions and your proposal.\n*   **Document Your Work:** Keep a detailed record of your contributions and your progress on your project. This will be helpful when writing your proposal and when reporting on your progress during the GSoC period.\n\nBy following these steps and consistently working hard, you'll significantly increase your chances of getting selected for a GSoC-like program. Good luck! Remember, it's a marathon, not a sprint. The learning and contribution is more valuable than the selection itself.\n",
